Happy flowering! 🌸

Like mother, like daughter. 🌸

I think this was our best year yet for ranunculus. 

Are y’all interested in a post of the different varieties we grew this year, and what I thought about the production of each?

The best re-use for a produce container is *drumroll* produce! 😜

I used to use ziploc bags with a paper towel to store strawberries, but these containers keep them from getting moldy or smashed, and so much fresher! 

Now I need all the ideas for how yall store your fresh harvests! Especially lettuce! Give me all the ideas!

Want a climbing rose that is almost thornless, repeat blooming, drought tolerant, pest tolerant, loves the south, and incredibly fast growing? 

Peggy Martin is your girl! 

Low maintenance, high impact and such a showstopper🌸

What are your favorite roses to grow? I try to add one or two every year to our garden and it’s so fun seeing them bloom!

Apricotta and double click cosmos are really starting to pop their gorgeous heads off! 

These were seed started indoors under grow lights in mid Feb and planted out after last frost in March!

Shirley poppies! One of the only flowers I grow here for no practical use besides beauty 🙌🏼

They don’t last long as cut flowers (maybe 2 days if you are lucky) BUT they bloom non stop in the garden for a few weeks. 

There are so many poppy varieties you could grow, but the Shirley ‘Supreme’ and Shirley ‘Falling in Love’ varieties top the list for me each year! 

I direct seed in October! 

Here’s what to do:
•poppy seeds are tiny, so I buy a big pack of them and use my hand to sprinkle literally hundreds over a certain area- don’t worry about it being too many! You can thin later on. 
•keep the seeded area damp until plants start to germinate
•once they have formed at least a few sets of leaves, I begin to “thin” mine (pull out seedlings so they don’t become too crowded)
•let them grow through winter, and in spring they will reward you with carefree, gorgeous blooms!

I’ll probably be kicked out of the gardening club for saying this but… Grow what actually makes sense for YOUR FAMILY, not what everyone else seems to grow. 

Last year I grew around 50 bulbs of garlic. And do you know how many I actually got around to using? 

Probably 10. 🤦🏼‍♀️

Most of it went to waste. 

Last year I realized I’m not really super great at prioritizing canning and preserving at this point in my life. 

It doesn’t feel worth the space in my garden or the time at home to prep garlic that I can buy organically at the store in a huge jar for just a few dollars. 

This year I planted 10 bulbs. And I will use 100% of them, AND was able to use my garden space more effectively for what I needed this year. 

Sometimes as gardeners, I think we tend to feel we have to grow certain things to be a “good” gardener. But the reality is that a good gardener, grows what they will use. 🪴
It feels great to personalize my garden to serve my needs, instead of the other way around. 

Today I harvested things that will all be used by the end of the week! 

Beets to add a kick to fresh summer smoothies, carrots for snacking, tomatoes for my lunch salad, and garlic + onions to put in our stir fry tonight! 

I love documenting what I’m growing and eating at different times of the year- it’s a fun practice to look back and see how it changes year to year. 💗

It’s always kind of incredible to me, that I can clip a bunch of garden stems, totally un-arranged in hand, and get something that looks like this 🌟 

I want to document a series called “the backyard bouquet” of flowers snipped from the garden that just so happen to look like perfection without the need of further human design. 

Nature is so rad. 

#thebackyardbouquet

Something that my husband and I do right after a wedding weekend that’s been super insightful for me…

Sitting down & adding up the hours of labor spent on various portions of the floristry process. ⏰ 

I’m always shocked at just how many hours are put in before I even design a single thing 🤯 

Things like:

• Consultations: in person/ virtually nailing down the brides vision for the day, budget, and thinking through alternatives that can fit within that budget. 

•ordering flowers 

•coordinating substitutions with wholesalers 

•tracking down local flower farms and checking flower availability 

•prepping flower buckets 

•unboxing 

•rose thorn stripping, leaf stripping, cutting, hydrating and all other flower prep. 

•sweeping up one zillion leaves and cut stems from the aftermath 🫠

A florist isn’t just charging you to simply buy and arrange flowers. 

They are charging you for all the hours before and after that are required to pull it off. 👏🏼🌸

Finally catching up on some long overdue flower work photo updates! 

This wedding for @camilledeckerhunt & @hadehunt was such a dream to be a part of. They thought of everything! 

The all white bridal + bridesmaid bouquets were so timeless🤍

Funny story-

This year, as I was running through a mental checklist of all the things I needed to do before our baby was born, I realized I had never planted out my ranunculus corms for the year. 

Sooo in my typical fashion, I planted the ranunculus corms this year the night before our baby was born about a month ago. 

At 1am…because that obviously seemed like a reasonable time to plant in the garden. 

Why is it that when I’m pregnant and something comes up on my to-do list, I have to do it RIGHT THEN or the world feels like it’ll crumble? 😂 

Anyone else this way??
